Randy,

The last communication from Mike Noble is below. I think at this point, my recommendation is to get the Card Connect
Term Sheet signed this week, so everyone knows we are serious. I am confident we can get to the finish line.

As I mentioned, we are going to play the “Good Cop” role in this negotiation with Noble…meaning we have to give a
little to get a little. With that, I think we can use the “Bad Cop” theme on a few items to push back to Noble without
appearing overly greedy.

Here is what I am thinking….

  1.  Mike will ask for a $1M incentive if he is able to complete integration to us by January 1, 2019. We should
      push back – “Mike, there is no way in hell we can commit to that kind of incentive without performance
      milestones along the way. We aren’t going to pay a $1M incentive simply for hitting a date without knowing
      the product is delivering the necessary revenue.”

We then come back with the following:
    *  $250k Integration Incentive – If you can complete the following… we will pay you within 30 days
        *   Milestone 1 – Live processing of new merchant accounts (meaning a merchant would decision on our
            tech/you tech question we discussed and board on the appropriate platform) by August 1, 2018
        *   Milestone 2 – Total monthly net revenue from combined new merchants boarded after August 1, 2018
            exceeds $100k/month by September 30, 2018
        *  Milestone 3 – Total monthly net revenue from combined new merchants boarded after August 1, 2018
            exceeds $200k/month by October 31, 2018.
        *  Milestone 4 – Total migration of Harbortouch Elavon portfolio to Shift4/Card Connect completed by
            December 1, 2018.

  2.  Mike will ask for an additional $1M incentive if he is able to complete the migration to Shift4 sooner than
      December 31, 2020. We should push back – “Seriously, we are paying you $35M in this transaction. That is
      already a huge incentive to get it done as fast as possible. Why should we have to pay more?”

We then come back with:

    *  We will incorporate $100k of additional consideration for every quarter you complete the migration of the
        entire portfolio in advance of December 31, 2020. For example, if you completed it by December 31,
        2019… we would pay a $400k incentive. I would use “Bad Cop” speak such as, “We have an obligation to
        our shareholders to operate profitably. The incentives must be somewhat tied to the increase profitability and
        cash flow we achieve from getting to Shift4 sooner. Also note, the Card Connect operating model is terrible,
        so we are taking a big hit here until all merchants are on Shift4.”

Please let me know your thoughts.

Thanks,

Jared

All,

I spoke with Mike Noble last night and again this morning. He is putting together a revised term sheet.

I have summarized my understanding of where we are at present:

    1.  Mike understands he will remain at Card Connect through Dec 2020 (minimum) unless we agree otherwise.
    2.  Mike understands there will be no additional compensation for the migration of Card Connect merchants to
        Shift4 from Jan 2021 – Dec 2024. I made it clear that we were ok with a best effort migration from that point
        forward.

I also said we need to begin generating at least $200k/month in net revenue on the new/combined platform with
Card Connect by Oct/Nov so we could achieve a reasonable payback on the acquisition cost. We all agreed this
should be possible because we are going to be doing a hard sales push between both channels (POS and middleware),
as a result of getting access to their gateway, and the many conversions from Harbortouch third party gateway
merchants.

    3. Mike understands there will some form of non-compete to follow for 2 years, but this is really just standard
       in an acquisition of this nature.

    4. Mike is going to make his best effort to try and get the reseller agreement signed by Friday.
    5. Mike is going to push hard to get a fully integrated Shift4/Card Connect new merchant boarding platform
       completed by the end of the year, so we can begin migrating Harbortouch Elavon merchants to the Card
       Connect/Shift4 platform.
    6.  Mike will be sending a term sheet that likely includes $1M+ accelerated migration incentive (to bring it all to
        Shift4 sooner) and $1M integration incentive (to get the new merchant platform combining both our
        technologies complete by the end of the year), so we can begin moving Harbortouch merchants.

I told him in my “Good Cop” tone to prepare for “Bad Cop” to come back and challenge some items in the terms
sheet, so he should make sure his ask is reasonable. I also mentioned we can’t reward him $1M just for completing
an integration milestone.

Overall, I am comfortable we can reign in the terms to something reasonable and get this done. We just need to
follow the “Good Cop/Bad Cop” script.

Thanks,

Jared

From: Jared Isaacman
Sent: Monday, May 07, 2018 11:47 AM
To: Randy Miskanic; Taylor Lavery
Cc: Nate Hirshman; Kyle Lutteroty; Daniel K. Devine
Subject: CardConnect

All,

I had a good call with Mike Noble at Card Connect this morning. Overall, I think it went well, and we covered
a lot of ground.

Here are the key takeaways…

1.  The reseller agreement looks pretty much done. Kyle is going to make another call to Mike to close out
    any remaining items. We should assume the deal is signed this week (as a reseller) and we can begin
    referring Card Connect business shortly thereafter.
2.  I covered the overall acquisition in detail with Mike. I introduced the idea of dividing the transaction
    into multiple parts. First, the Reseller period. Second, a short exclusivity period (30-45 days) where
    we would come to terms on an overall plan to migrate all Card Connect Customers to Shift4 over a
    multi-year period. Last, implementation of the plan with an ultimate sunset to that migration period at the
    end of 2024.
3.  Mike introduced the idea of a $35M acquisition price, which I agreed seemed reasonable for the ~$6M in
    net revenue run rate of their book. I mentioned that the only way that valuation worked was if we had a
    plan in place to move all those customers to Shift4 and within a reasonable timeframe. We also agreed
    that paying incentives at the end of a 3-4 year migration period would be less desirable to both him and
    us. Mike agreed there was a lot of synergy between our organizations. He said, “We can create a lot of
    shareholder value between our two companies.”
4.  I mentioned we would not be able to keep merchants on the old Card Connect platform indefinitely. This
    didn’t seem to bother Mike. We discussed having a plan in place to convey to the agents and merchants
    that there will be great new products + incentives to move to Shift4 and for those that chose to remain
    behind, it was very likely their pricing would increase substantially – as will no longer be supporting that
    technology long term.

    **Overall, I was trying to make it clear there were two parts to this transaction. First, a short term reseller
    agreement while we completed a plan that supported a $35M acquisition price. Second, an
    implementation component, which included completing a middleware “tech to tech” integration between
    our companies. The acquisition would be contingent on the successful completion of the plan and an
    implementation that was acceptable to both organizations.

    This is important because it gives us plenty of outs if they don’t deliver what is needed from our
    technical assessment.**

5.  Mike is going to send a term sheet later this week that will include an incentive component for
    the additional revenue that is generated from integrating our technologies together. For example,
    making Harbortouch and a number of the middleware POS systems that we work with compatible
    with Card Connect should yield considerable incremental revenue. We discussed an incentive
    component tied to this additional revenue.
6.  I said we would likely pay a portion of the transaction price in cash and the remainder in stock. This
    didn’t seem to bother Mike, as he mentioned there were members of the organization that were
    already shareholders in the company.
7.  Mike also mentioned the Harbortouch-Elavon portfolio many times. I believe he is assuming that as a
    result of this overall acquisition, that we would begin migrating Harbortouch-Elavon merchants to Card
    Connect during the “implementation phase.” I didn’t commit to that in any way, other than to say
    we were working towards a single platform solution, but it was never expressly stated that we would
    move Harbortouch-Elavon merchants to Card Connect.
8.  Mike seemed very excited when I shared the capabilities within the reseller agreement to put the
    Harbortouch gateway and third-party POS systems on Card Connect. He said, “This is a game changer”
    and would come with significant cost savings.
9. Mike is going to try and connect with Frank on the gateway. He will also reach out to Sam to answer
    any remaining questions, in terms of the integration capabilities of Card Connect.
10. Mike is going to begin working with their team to establish a timeline for integrating the Shift4
    middleware to Card Connect. I mentioned we should assume we will be integrating to multiple
    processors even after such a transaction is completed. We discussed using the same format as we
    do with our existing gateway partners.
11. I did mention to Mike, that should we get to a final executable agreement to acquire the company, that we
    have to be able to get terms in there that allow us an out in case of a material adverse change in their
    business (attrition) between contract signing and closing. He did agree with that.

I am ok with the $35M provided it includes an acceptable plan to get merchants converted to
Shift4/Dollars-on-the-Net within 4 years. I think an approach, like the one mentioned above, gives us the
flexibility to make a thorough technical assessment before committing to any acquisition. I think we should
expect a Term Sheet from Mike soon. We will follow our “Good Cop/Bad Cop” approach (I’m Good Cop of
course) in order to arrive at something reasonable.

Please give me a call if you have any questions.

Thanks,

Jared

From: Jared Isaacman
Sent: Tuesday, April 10, 2018 10:28 PM
To: Randy Miskanic; Taylor Lavery
Cc: Nate Hirshman; Kyle Lutteroty; Daniel K. Devine
Subject: CardConnect

All,

I had another call with Mike Noble at Card Connect today. Here is a summary…

  1.  Overall, I think it was very productive. We covered a lot of ground in a short period of time and if all
      goes as planned, we could have a big win before the end of the month.
  2.  I began the call by discussing the present state of the payment industry and, again, sharing our long-term
      vision to ultimately move to just a single platform. I said we just want to do business with good
      people/companies, be fair and reasonable… but ultimately we need to get to just one platform. I also told him
      how important the next ~30-45 days were for us in defining our long-term strategy.
  3.  I told him we were absolutely not going to achieve our long-term vision by integrating to every single
      payment gateway on earth. I am sure he knows that Card Connect is a payment gateway. I said, “We just
      aren’t going to have 50-100 payment gateways. It’s absurd. It’s not going to happen.” I also said, “There are
      only a few gateways out there than can likely meet all our long-term needs.”
  4.  I asked Mike if we could resell Card Connect with our present gateway environment. He said we absolutely
      could, as that is their business model. I went back to him that there are only a few companies on this planet
      that do what they are doing, so I just want to make sure before we go down a path that introduces a lot of
      complexity down the line. He said there are no restrictions.
  5.  After getting through the above, I made it pretty clear we have to get some wins here. I can’t go back to
      them and say we connected Shift4 to Card Connect and now we have 10 payment gateways when our plan
      is to get that number to 1. That isn’t a win.
  6.  I said we absolutely could send them business now – as that is their model, but that isn’t a huge win. Mike
      said, “There is a bigger play here.”
  7.  I told Mike, “We are consolidating the payment industry.” I said we have to do it in a way in which everyone
      wins throughout the process, but we absolutely are consolidating the industry because it is absurd and
      inefficient at present.
      I also said, “It’s just a question of whether we are along for the ride with you on that journey.”
  8.  That is when I introduced the topic of acquiring the entire company. I said, “We would rather just buy the
      entire company.” I told him, “It just makes the most sense for us.”
  9. He was not surprised at all by this. He actually sounded excited by the idea. He mentioned that he
      believed there was a lot of synergy between our two organizations and referenced opportunities to cross-
      sell products, etc…
 10. He did mention the Card Connect gateway is also used within their enterprise solutions group. I should have
      clarified what that meant, but didn’t. I am sure they don’t use it for tolling, parking, etc… which is what they
      likely consider enterprise. It is probably Oracle, SAP, etc… integrations.
 11. I said, “I don’t know what your financials look like.” He offered to share them with me.
 12. I also mentioned there are a lot of creative ways we could structure a transaction to make it a win for all parties.
      He mentioned a fair valuation would be around 5x their current net revenue.
 13. He is going to look for a time to talk again this week to further discuss this. I have a feeling we will be crafting
      a plan within the next few weeks.

I think this could be a huge opportunity. I could certainly use the “Good Cop / Bad Cop” routine effectively here.

Please let me know your thoughts.

Thanks,

Jared
